Building A Report From The R Markdown Template

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

This document is created directly from the original RStudio R Markdown template. I simply typed in all the text you see below to replace the summary of cars and the graph of pressure.

Instead of printing out a summary of the cars dataset, Ive modified the default template here to get some selected bits of weather from London City Airport, and print them out instead. Dont get hung up on the

options(geonamesUsername="rstudio_dashboard")    #  Login name for geonames
LCY_observation    <- GNweatherIcao("EGLC")      # EGLC is London City
london_weather <- LCY_observation %>%            # Extract 5 columns
    select(stationName, datetime, temperature, humidity)
print(london_weather)
##           stationName            datetime temperature humidity
## 1 London City Airport 2019-09-04 12:20:00          20       42

Inserting Links to Other Sites

Its easy to include links to other sites. Simply put the text you want displayed in square brackets, followed by the target URL of the site in normal parentheses. Your link codeshould look like this:

[Text you want displayed for the link](https://link-target)

So to link to the BBC London Weather, youd use this code:

[BBC London Weather](https://www.bbc.com/weather/2643743)

When its knit, this is what your link will look like.

BBC London Weather

Inserting Local Images

Local images are easy to include in R Markdown. The general form is as follows:

![Alternate text for image](path/to/image.png)

So to include an image of the London skyline that Ive conveniently stored in the images directory for this R project, Id write

![*London Skyline*](images/london_skyline.png)

Heres what that photo looks like:

London Skyline

Getting Images From Other Sites

But what if you dont a copy of the image you want to include, but you know its available on the internet? In that case, you can use either the same insert the R function include_graphics from the knitr package.

knitr::include_graphics("https://www.cpc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/JAWF_Monitoring/Europe/daily/p.1day.figa.gif")

You can also embed dynamic images, provided that the web site returns the image a .png, a .jpg, or a .gif object. Heres a real-time satellite image.

knitr::include_graphics("https://en.sat24.com/image?type=visual&region=gb")
